{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"cd4df83d-d3d2-4b62-8cf1-977f793d6d97","content":"The directory doesn't exist yet, but here's what you need to configure in your `.csproj` to publish as a dotnet tool:\n\n### Required `.csproj` properties\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n  <PackAsTool>true</PackAsTool>\n  <ToolCommandName>my-mcp-server</ToolCommandName>\n\n  <!-- NuGet metadata -->\n  <PackageId>MyMcpServer</PackageId>\n  <Version>1.0.0</Version>\n  <Authors>YourName</Authors>\n  <Description>An MCP server using stdio transport.</Description>\n  <PackageLicenseExpression>MIT</PackageLicenseExpression>\n  <PackageReadmeFile>README.md</PackageReadmeFile>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n- **`PackAsTool`** — marks the project as a .NET tool.\n- **`ToolCommandName`** — the CLI command users run after installing.\n- **`OutputType` must be `Exe`** — tools must be console apps.\n\n### Publish steps\n\n```bash\n# Pack\ndotnet pack -c Release\n\n# Push (one-time: get an API key from nuget.org)\ndotnet nuget push bin/Release/MyMcpServer.1.0.0.nupkg \\\n  --api-key YOUR_API_KEY --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\n### Users install with\n\n```bash\ndotnet tool install --global MyMcpServer\nmy-mcp-server   # runs via stdio\n```\n\nThat's the minimal setup. Want me to create or update your actual `.csproj` file?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"9002cfc0-73fe-4903-bba1-7dacc0fc52a1","outputTokens":416,"requestId":"CC22:281228:C0AC84:DF463F:69EAC1CF"},"id":"cc539a59-b410-4d90-ab9a-641f1fedebdd","timestamp":"2026-04-24T01:05:27.618Z","parentId":"e67790a6-d940-4fd5-b49f-9616519e3bdf"}
